Premium categories here are low volume and should not carry high safety stock.
Conclusion:
Budget makeup and declining budget skincare should be stocked cautiously with tighter replenishment triggers and potential range rationalization.

Recommended Next Actions
1. Immediate Action (Next 7 Days)
Protect Premium Skincare availability in East and North.

Expedite delayed East shipment.
Reallocate excess premium skincare stock (if available) from South/West to East/North.
Temporarily prioritize production capacity to premium skincare.
2. Medium-Term Action (Next 30 Days)
Reset safety stock and replenishment parameters by segment:

High-priority SKUs: increase safety stock and service targets (e.g., 95–98%).
Medium-priority SKUs: maintain current policy (90–95%).
Low-priority SKUs: reduce reorder quantities and lower target cover to avoid overstock.
3. Stock Policy Alignment Issue
Service Level Differentiation by Margin and Demand Strength

Currently, products are treated too uniformly.
Supply Chain, Sales, and Inventory teams must align on:

Higher service targets and faster replenishment for high-margin, growth SKUs (Premium Skincare).
Controlled, lean stocking strategy for declining budget makeup.
Clear agreement that not all SKUs require the same availability target.
Without this alignment, working capital will continue flowing into slow movers while high-margin SKUs face stockout risk.

Management Takeaway
Biggest Risk: Stockouts in Premium Skincare (East & North).
Biggest Working Capital Drain: Budget Makeup with declining demand and >25–30 days cover.
Strategic Shift Needed: Move from uniform stock rules to differentiated, margin- and demand-based inventory strategy.
